response:
Run a randomized within-subject study: developers debug matched bug sets with and without rubber ducking, with order counterbalanced. Metric: median time to first correct bug identification, plus bugs found in 30 minutes. Hypothesis: verbalizing to a duck reduces time to correct identification versus silent debugging. Confounders: bug difficulty, developer experience, fatigue, learning effects, and prior familiarity with the code. Control these by matching tasks, randomization, counterbalancing, and blocking on experience. Stopping rule: stop at a preregistered sample size from power analysis or at an interim futility boundary.
Bottom line:
A controlled randomized debugging study can test whether rubber ducking improves bug-finding speed.
